  "general_form": "AB(aq) + CD(aq) -> AD(s) + CB(aq)",
  "summary": "Two soluble salts swap partners, and one new pairing is insoluble — it drops out as a solid precipitate. The solubility rules decide which pairing is the solid, and the net-ionic equation strips away the spectator ions to show only the ions that actually combine. No element goes free, so precipitation is not a redox reaction.",
  "regime": "rule-sourced",
  "source": "openstax-chemistry-2e",
  "conditions": [
    "Both reactants dissolved (aqueous); the driving force is that one product is insoluble.",
    "Which product is insoluble comes from the sourced solubility rules — the engine classifies it, it is not guessed."
  ],
  "misconceptions": [
    {
      "claim": "The spectator ions disappear once the precipitate forms.",
      "refute": "Spectator ions stay dissolved and are still there — the complete-ionic equation shows them on both sides, and the net-ionic equation cancels them because they are unchanged, not gone."
    },
    {
      "claim": "The reactant present in the smaller amount is what limits the precipitate.",
      "refute": "Amount alone does not decide it — the mole ratio does. Run the ledger: the reactant that runs out first at the balanced ratio is limiting, which can be the one you have more of."
    }
  ],
